05766nam a22008175i 9783110891379DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20142002gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979693372  a97831108913797 a10.1515/97831108913792doi  a(DE-B1597)56100  a(OCoLC)924083561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS2555.52b.H88 2002eb 7aREL0061002bisacsh04a226.062231 aHultgren, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarrative Elements in the Double Tradition :bA Study of Their Place within the Framework of the Gospel Narrative /cStephen Hultgren.  aReprint 2014 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (420 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v11300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction to the Problem: Narrative Elements in the Double Tradition -- t1. Historical Overview: The Genesis of a False Dichotomy -- t2. Are You the One to Come? On the Relationship between John the Baptist and Jesus (Matt 11.2-6, 7-11//Luke 7.18-23, 24-28) -- t3. The Obedient Son of God: The Temptation and the Passion (Matt 4.1-11//Luke 4.1-13) -- t4. From Nazareth to Capernaum: The Beginning of the Galilean Ministry (Matt 4.12-16; Luke 4.14-31 a) -- t5. The Early Galilean Ministry (in and around Capernaum) -- t6. The Later Galilean and Judean Ministries -- t7. The Passion Narrative -- t8. Narrative Elements in the Double Tradition: Conclusions and Implications -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Scripture References -- tIndex of Other Ancient Sources -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor a long time mainstream gospel scholarship has assumed that the so-called Q material (the "double tradition") in Matthew and Luke represents a document or tradition that was almost exclusively orientated towards the sayings of Jesus of Nazareth, with little interest in a narrative about him. This book argues, on the contrary, that the narrative material in the double tradition existed from the very beginning within a coherent Jesus narrative that ran from his baptism to his passion. Far from being inserted by Matthew and Luke into the framework of Mark, the double tradition is structured on the very same narrative framework as the Gospel of Mark (a framework that predates Mark). Conventional dichotomies in gospel origins, the historical Jesus, and the history of early Christianity are thus drawn into question.  aLange Zeit ist die Forschung zu den Evangelien davon ausgegangen, daß das sog. Q-Material im Matthäus- und Lukasevangelium eine Quelle oder eine Tradition darstellt, die fast ausschließlich an den Logien Jesu von Nazareth interessiert war, kaum dagegen an Erzählungen über ihn. Die vorliegende Studie zeigt demgegenüber, daß das Erzählgut in Q von Anfang an existierte, und zwar innerhalb einer Jesus-Erzählung, die von seiner Taufe bis zur Passion reichte. Dieser Erzählrahmen gleicht demjenigen von Markus, ist aber älter. Matthäus und Lukas haben das Q-Material keineswegs in den Erzählrahmen von Markus eingefügt. Die bisherigen differenzierten Forschungspositionen zur Entstehung der Evangelien, zum historischen Jesus und zur Geschichte des frühen Christentums stehen dabei zur Diskussion.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aQ hypothesis (Synoptics criticism). 0aSynoptic problem. 0aTwo source hypothesis (Synoptics criticism). 4aNarrative Exegese. 4aZweiquellentheorie. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA B